    12                          ; even the complication of paging the kernal ROM in and out, so it doesn't need
    13                          ; the cache which the C64 code uses when ALLMEM is defined. SFTODO: SAY SOMETHING ABOUT ACORN_TURBO_SUPPORTED
    14                          ;
    15                          ; The sideways RAM build (ifdef ACORN_SWR) is a bit more involved. The hardware
    16                          ; situation here is that we have main RAM (not paged) from $0000-$7fff
    17                          ; inclusive, with user RAM starting at OSHWM/PAGE, which varies between machines
    18                          ; but will typically be in the range $e00-$1f00. Some builds hard-code a certain
    19                          ; address, others use acorn-relocate.asm to accommodate this variation. We also
    20                          ; have up to 16 different 16K banks of "sideways" RAM paged in at $8000-$bfff
    21                          ; inclusive. (The BBC series and Electron have different ways to control paging;
    22                          ; see the acorn_page_in_bank_* macros.) The OS is not paged and lives
    23                          ; permanently at $c000-$ffff inclusive. The loader will have located any
    24                          ; available sideways RAM banks, verified there's at least one and put the count
    25                          ; and a list of bank numbers at ram_bank_{count,list} for us. SFTODO: MINOR QUIBBLE - LOADER WILL HAVE VERIFIED WE HAVE ENOUGH SWR BANKS, THERE MAY BE NONE IF WE CAN GET BY WITHOUT ANY
    26                          ;
    27                          ; Acorn Ozmoo uses two slightly different sideways RAM models. Both of them
    28                          ; allow static/high memory to be spread over approximately 9 sideways RAM banks
    29                          ; (indexed in 512-byte chunks with indexes from 0-254, with chunk 0 starting
    30                          ; at story_start+nonstored_blocks). The standard Ozmoo mempointer (data) and 
    31                          ; z_pc_mempointer (Z-machine PC) pointers are extended to each have an associated
    32                          ; RAM bank (mempointer_ram_bank and z_pc_mempointer_ram_bank respectively). (If
    33                          ; the relevant byte of Z-machine memory lives in main RAM, the bank number is
    34                          ; irrelevant as main RAM is not affected by paging.)
    35                          ;
    36                          ; The "big dynamic RAM" model (ifndef ACORN_SWR_SMALL_DYNMEM) allows the game's
    37                          ; dynamic memory (which starts in main RAM at story_start, as on any Ozmoo build)
    38                          ; to be larger than main RAM and overflow into the first 16K sideways RAM bank.
    39                          ; The first 16K sideways RAM bank therefore has to be paged in by default, so
    40                          ; that miscellaneous Ozmoo code which might try to access dynamic memory can do
    41                          ; so without any trouble. In this model, accesses to memory via read_next_byte
    42                          ; and read_next_byte_at_z_pc temporarily page in the relevant bank to read the
    43                          ; byte and then page the first 16K sideways RAM bank back in. (As an
    44                          ; optimisation, read_next_byte_at_z_pc_unsafe* and friends are used during
    45                          ; instruction decoding to avoid flipping back and forth excessively while
    46                          ; reading a multi-byte instruction. This is possible because only a very limited
    47                          ; set of cases can cause accesses to dynamic memory during instruction decoding.)
    48                          ;
    49                          ; The "small dynamic RAM" model (ifdef ACORN_SWR_SMALL_DYNMEM) requires the game's
    50                          ; dynamic memory to fit in main RAM. Since dynamic memory can then be accessed
    51                          ; regardless of the currently paged in bank, Ozmoo instead keeps the bank
    52                          ; containing the Z-machine's PC paged in by default, temporarily paging it out
    53                          ; only when reading a data byte.
    54                          ;
    55                          ; On a second processor or BBC series machine with shadow RAM, screen RAM is
    56                          ; separate from user RAM and doesn't get in the way. On a BBC B with no shadow
    57                          ; RAM, we use a trick (see ACORN_NO_SHADOW) to relocate the 1K screen RAM to
    58                          ; $3c00, leave a gap in the Ozmoo binary to accommodate that and we can then
    59                          ; mostly forget about screen RAM. Dynamic memory starts at story_start just
    60                          ; after the Ozmoo stack (as on the C64) and is followed (with suitable paging
    61                          ; for ACORN_SWR) directly by the virtual memory cache.
    62                          ;
    63                          ; On the Electron shadow RAM is rare and we can't use the ACORN_NO_SHADOW trick
    64                          ; to get the screen memory (8K, from $6000-$8000) out of the way. Ozmoo really
    65                          ; wants dynamic memory to be contiguous, and there isn't really enough RAM free
    66                          ; between the Ozmoo stack and the screen memory to run all the games we'd like
    67                          ; to. We therefore compromise by forcing the use of the big dynamic RAM model
    68                          ; and making dynamic RAM start at $8000 instead of following the Ozmoo stack.
    69                          ; This limits us to 16K of dynamic memory, which isn't too bad (and is more than
    70                          ; we'd have free below screen RAM). We use the main RAM between the Ozmoo stack
    71                          ; and the screen RAM as additional virtual memory cache so it isn't wasted. An
    72                          ; Electron is therefore about 7K worse off than a BBC B with the same amount of
    73                          ; sideways RAM as a result of its larger screen memory, in addition to not
    74                          ; supporting games needing more than 16K of dynamic memory. The Electron save/
    75                          ; restore code has to be slightly different because the data we need to save/
    76                          ; restore is no longer contiguous in memory.
    77                          
    78                          ; To improve readability of code and avoid double-nesting so we can test for
    79                          ; ACORN_SWR and !ACORN_SWR_SMALL_DYNMEM in a single !ifdef, we define
    80                          ; ACORN_SWR_BIG_DYNMEM internally - the build script should never set this.
    81                          !ifdef ACORN_SWR {
    82                          !ifndef ACORN_SWR_SMALL_DYNMEM {
    83                          ACORN_SWR_BIG_DYNMEM = 1
    84                          } else { ; ACORN_SWR_SMALL_DYNMEM
    85                          !ifdef ACORN_ELECTRON_SWR {
    86                          !error "ACORN_ELECTRON_SWR is not compatible with ACORN_SWR_SMALL_DYNMEM"
    87                          }
    88                          }
    89                          }
